<A NAME = "38"></A>Copyright
WORLD TAX REPORT via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

AUSTRALIA: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT CONCESSION

The government has announced changes to the research and development
(R&D) tax concession, which provides a 150 per cent deduction for
eligible R&D expenditures, to combat 'gravedigging' practices designed
to exploit the concession.

The 'gravedigging' practice involves consultants examining company
records for previous years' expenditures that might qualify for the
special deduction and applying long after the fact for recognition of
expenses as R&D outlays.

Under the new rules, registration for the concession must take place
within six months of the end of the year in which the expenses were
incurred. Transitional arrangements will allow registration of expenses
incurred in the 1993-94 tax year and the 1994-95 tax year (ending 30
June 1995) until 30 June 1996. Expenses incurred prior to 1 July 1993
will no longer be eligible for the concession.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
